SIMPLE: satisfy
RECORDS: 2

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Satisfy
<hw>Sat"is*fy</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. &
p. p.</pos> <conjf>Satisfied</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb.
n.</pos> <conjf>Satisfying</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>.]</vmorph> <ety>[OF.
<ets>satisfier</ets>; L. <ets>satis</ets> enough + <ets>-ficare</ets>
(in comp.) to make; cf. F. <ets>satisfaire</ets>, L.
<ets>satisfacere</ets>. See <er>Sad</er>, <pos>a.</pos>, and
<er>Fact</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>In general, to fill up the
measure of a want of (a person or a thing); hence, to gratify fully the
desire of; to make content; to supply to the full, or so far as to give
contentment with what is wished for.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Death shall . . . with us two⟦br⟧
Be forced to <qex>satisfy</qex> his ravenous maw.</q>
<rj><qau>Milton.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To pay to the extent of claims or deserts; to give
what is due to; <as>as, to <ex>satisfy</ex> a creditor</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>To answer or discharge, as a claim, debt, legal
demand, or the like; to give compensation for; to pay off; to requite;
<as>as, to <ex>satisfy</ex> a claim or an execution</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>To free from doubt, suspense, or uncertainty; to
give assurance to; to set at rest the mind of; to convince; <as>as, to
<ex>satisfy</ex> one's self by inquiry</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The standing evidences of the truth of the gospel are in
themselves most firm, solid, and <qex>satisfying</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Atterbury.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><syn><b>Syn.</b> -- To satiate; sate; content; grafity; compensate.
See <er>Satiate</er>.</syn>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Satisfy</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Satisfy
<hw>Sat"is*fy</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To
give satisfaction; to afford gratification; to leave nothing to be
desired.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To make payment or atonement; to atone.</def>
<rj><au>Milton.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Satisfyingly</ent>⟦br⟧
